Somehow already a week has past since having the opportunity to give a talk at @createcultivate’s Future Summit.
☀️
The topic was on “Using Mindfulness to Fuel Innovation” and the idea is actually simple in nature, though can be difficult to commit to.
❤️‍🔥
We addressed the fact that the wondrous form of creativity that we know as innovation… rarely arises in 30min zoom meeting blocks. Or under the pressures of deadlines. Or under the watchful eye of managers.
💓
We often have our best ideas in the shower or on a walk or when we are just about to fall asleep or wake up.
🪐
Why IS that?
It’s because innovation is… creative energy in motion. And that motion only is available to us when we are… relaxed.
🐠
A fish can’t swim in ice.
Our best ideas can’t arise under duress.
🌊
Together, this incredible group of female entrepreneurs leaned in, courageously stepped into a @theclass shaking practice with me, dropped in a mantra to help wrangle the mind, and took home tools for how to access this creative freedom for when they are back in daily grind.
🪩
You don’t need a vacation every time you need or want to innovate. (I mean, that helps, don’t get me wrong.) All you need is a good song, a strong shake, a deep breath, and a willing heart. Repeat after me : all is welcome.
✨✨✨✨✨✨
Thank you so much to @createcultivate for having me, to @katelenelise and @jaclynrjohnson for welcoming me into C&C, to @jilllindsey and @k_cavs for supporting me in my preparation, and to this wonderful room of humans who were so engaged, so curious, and such a joy to work with.

My biggest takeaway from @kevinjcourtney’s 7-days, deep dive retreat into the precise and powerful practices of Pratyahara, is that our mind will follow our sensory cravings and addictions & that our sensory cravings and addictions will follow our mind. The two are inextricably linked. 

I loved that the senses are defined with so much more depth than the 5 we are accustomed to. They not only include what we ingest, but also impressions from the media, movies, tech, social networks. As well as associations - the relationships we keep or don’t keep. 

“Withdraw the mind from unhealthy foods, impressions, and associations & we gain the power to meet, face, and conquer our sensorial addictions.”

With skill, which is to say, with practice, the mind can unhook from chasing these cravings, slow, soften, release, and quiet long enough for us to experience a connection much greater and more profound than our mind can manage. Some call this Source.

@kevinjcourtney worked on this retreat for just about an entire year, as he makes his way through The Eightfold Path deeply investigating one limb of yoga each year, over the course of 7 years. His devotion to studentship, to these teachings, and to the care and precision with which he brings people into an experience is something I not only whole heartedly love about him, but something I deeply deeply respect. 

Each day was so intentionally curated with lecture, practice, and supportive experiences led by @erin_rose_ward @erinyeehealingarts @kaceofbase @__propheta__ @yinsteryogi. And I snuck in there to lead a night of storytelling inspired by @mothstories (@hdawgcolvin !). 

Thank you to each of you masterful facilitators, to @menlaretreat, to @simonevavra @karey__edwards, and to this high caliber community of The Eightfold Path, for creating such an impressive and impactful body of work. I’ll never forget the last practice, feeling completely and holistically … at peace.

🪐

ON FRIENDSHIP
“A friend knows our difficulties and shadows and remains in sight, a companion to our vulnerabilities more than our triumphs, when we are under the strange illusion we do not need them.” - David Whyte
✨
I met @deeniewrites 15 years ago. I started with @theclass 10 years ago. Back then, we didn’t have a teacher training program. Taryn and I trusted that there might be a way for me to teach this in the future & so I set her Classes up, broke them down, and took notes on the subway ride to my two other jobs on what was happening in my body and in her guidance.
✨
Armed with a tiny Bluetooth speaker, a well-worn notebook, and the public lawn of Fort Greene Park, I asked 3 close friends to be my guinea pigs week after week, to let me try teaching on, to give me raw feedback, and to support me in the vulnerability of not knowing what I was doing.
✨
Deenie was one of those 3 friends (🫶@catalinaphotog @jess.halliburton). And in this very raw, very courageous essay, she writes about our friendship, the changing shape of The Class, her initiation into motherhood, and our vulnerabilities that had their own seasonalities throughout the last 10years.
✨
I hope you’ll give it a read. I wonder if you’ll relate.
✨
Deenie, always… thank you for the gift of your words, your honesty, your friendship.
💓

On this threshold of 38, I don’t want this or a that (though either or both would be nice 😝). I want to remember each day that this day isn’t guaranteed. It’s gifted. Season 6 Episode 11: Natalie Kuhn #linkinbio for full episode 💙⁠
⁠
Natalie Kuhn is Co-CEO and a founding teacher of The Class. Listen in as she shares about spirituality, the human body, and the incredible healing power of expression.⁠
⁠
While Natalie grew up with Catholicism and Buddhism, it was in her biology class that she realized the profound power of the spiritual nature of life. Natalie saw the power of the human body to heal as a doorway to the mystery of the unseen power of spirituality. In her work today, the power of her spiritual insight has come full circle in her work in The Class. It truly is a physical, emotional, intellectual, and spiritual expression of the reach of Natalie’s love’s everyday radius.⁠
⁠
In this conversation with Liz, Natalie speaks a lot about the power of expression. During her week at the Process, she discovered that all of her emotions were finally set free when she was able to express the fullness of her anger through her cathartic work there. She goes on to tell us how expression frees emotion, which frees our vitality, life force, and creativity. In other words, it frees our Spirit. Natalie found that her work at the Process brought even more of her vitality and joy to her work with people and The Class.⁠
⁠
Tag along on this joyful ride with Natalie and Liz, and stay with them to the end. You’ll be glad you did because Natalie had a special gift for you.
⁠

I just got back to our apartment in brooklyn.

6.5 weeks ago, we got the news of Kevin’s cancer diagnosis. I was in Europe and he was in LA. I hopped the first flight to NY to quickly pack a carry on bag and pick up Smooch, to then get the next flight to LA.

Walking in here, to brooklyn for the first time since, feels like a time wrap. Like I walked into a time capsule of our old life. All of it the way it was - and all of the ways we were - before the diagnosis.

And it feels like grief - not of a person - but of a version of our lives. This apartment looks and feels like a chapter that has ended. The book I was reading before we left on our trips, still on the nightstand. The puppy pee pad we were training smooch with, unused on the floor. Half a carton of oat milk in the fridge.

Sometimes life happens in such a big urgent and immediate way that some part of us gets frozen in time while another leaps ahead. And only in more time will one thaw and the other slow. Integration can’t be forced. 

For now, I’m here for the next few days to pick up some pieces, pack a few boxes, say hello to old faces, and retrace a few steps. Back and forth we go.

Grief isn’t always for a being’s passing. It can also be for a way that’s changing before we were ready.

The word “apocalypse”comes from Ancient Greek “apokalypsis,” meaning:
 
* to uncover
* to reveal 
* to lay bare

What if, when something feels apocalyptic, we reframed our approach to it and saw it as an opportunity to discover something hidden underneath?

Every Retreatment has a map. This 5-day journey in Italy had a very specific one: soften the nervous system enough to make contact with our inner child. Listen to them, give them an outlet, offer your hand, and then let them PLAY… for the sake of our quality of life.

Each day started with a different meditation curated for the days work led by Alison Sinatra. Then, I’d share a 30-45min talk on how the nervous system, our ego, our behaviors and the inward calling from our sweet little single-digit child are all interconnected. After, we stepped into a 2 hour somatic practice of @theclass to discover it for ourselves + where it lives in the body.

Nourishing meals (read: 🍝) give way to afternoons curated for where we are in the map’s arc, using yin yoga, holotropic breathwork and sharing circles guided by Alison and an epic gong bath by @gongheart.

Closing with one of the most powerful sacred circles I’ve experienced in the ten years of The Retreatment. If we can soften enough, rest enough, and learn to listen - it’s that sweet little voice that got lodged in our nervous systems all those decades ago that holds the key to our healthy and conscious maturation.

🙏
@alison.sinatra : thank you for making it so easy to collaborate, for the laughter, the partnership, and the prayers.

To the team : @emkron @katelady @mallorymeeks @alisonmccleawolper @mandali_retreats thank you for the collaboration, the love, the care, the above and beyond efforts.

To @_courtneycrowley_ @cristina_pacheco : thank you for the months and months of organization, seen and unseen, that scaffolded this journey.

This community ranged from 15 years old to 60s, representing about 13 different countries, committed and willing to go deep, uphold kindness + integrity as core values, and support each other in doing the work of healing & self-exploration. It was a wonder to behold.

To you, Italy 2023 community : I love you & I love you back. Thank you for your trust, integrity, courage, and kindness. May our thread never end & may the kiddos keep playing. 🪁

It truly is an honor and a privilege to get to do this work alongside @theclass team and community. Deeply deeply grateful. 

🏹 Love Nat

My becoming

We all have those patterns that are super old, that are no longer serving us, and that are affecting our personal and professional lives. And if we don’t address them well, they end up driving us and determining our future. But if we do turn toward them in a good way, we have the opportunity to place ourselves in the drivers seat where we can be the ones to shape our future.

At @theclass, we offer a 4-day program once a year called The Immersion, to do just that. Step away from your life, peel your cheek off of the windshield, get some distance - some perspective - and find the root of the pattern in the body, in community, in practice. I’m never more aware of my own mortality than when I witness Kevin come face to face with his. 

Sometimes I forget that he’s got cancer. Maybe it’s because he looks and feels so much healthier these days than in the years before. Maybe it’s because we are both fully committed to and focused on a full recovery. Maybe its my own heart’s survival tactic. 

Every two weeks on Monday morning, 
if I have forgotten, the infusions are 
where the reminder comes back in full force. 

And importance periscopes.  Attention realigns. 

And I cross that threshold through 
The Door of What Matters

again

The doorway that I would not otherwise 
pass through as frequently, 
if I weren’t bearing witness to him.

🫶

Starting 10/1, “The Class for the BIPOC Community” will launch, led by our BIPOC teachers, and continue on the first Sunday of each month. This long-term and long overdue Class is dedicated to creating sacred spaces for BIPOC students to practice @theclass together in person & in community. 

We have the honor of @amandarose4209 kicking things off in LA and @aimee_mere leading in NY. 

The creation of this sacred space has been shaped by the continued care, passion, conversation, partnership, and love of @mslindalopes @rawbabysugar @amandarose4209 @aimee_mere. In the coming months, they will be joined by @cjfrogozo @thebentandthestraight and @sophiamanassei . I and all at The Class support this offering with all of our being so that we can continue to see The Class become an ever-evolving, more welcoming place.

What I’m learning everyday is that change doesn’t happen because you say you want it. And a space isn’t actually safe just because you say it is. Both are a result of deep listening, honest conversations, care, collaboration, messing up, getting up, partnership, shared vision, small consistent actions, that culminate and become the shape of it. Words are tired if the environment doesn’t evolve. 

This launch is one of joy and celebration. It is a powerful step as a result of cumulative care. It is a privilege to work alongside this team of teachers who pour their artistry and dedication into this method and who are creating this space for the BIPOC Community to practice in a way that feels most welcoming and most supportive. It’s a core value of this company to become more inclusive, and these monthly Classes are an important step in its mission and vision.

I’m so proud to support the launch and the ongoing offering of The Class for the BIPOC Community. May the world of The Class continue to become a safer, more inclusive place of practice and community!

❤️

All the threads of our life
(Work, relationship, self) work on us like currents of wind, pushing and pulling on us, surrounding and informing us, according to our unique spiritual makeup. 

It becomes important to those who are interested in living a more awake and/or fulfilling life to become familiar… even intimate… with those currents so that we can direct them. 

Not control them.
Direct them. 

As if each one were a sail of a boat, each responding uniquely to the conditions based on their dimensions and purpose, each with a connection to the sailor who isn’t fighting the weather

But directing the sail
To navigate the wind

At the end of the work week, whether it was that particular email thread or a coworkers bad day, we know that our bodies can be here but our hearts and minds can be stalled in neutral, or have taken on water, or worse… absent. 

And in the intimacy of admitting where the parts of ourselves are dispersed, we can begin to call ourselves back. 

Directing our sails
Back towards home. 

*

We’ll do just that in @theclass today at 11:30am PT. “See” you soon.

The Retreatment Yucatan had been on the books for months. Never could we have predicted that 3 weeks before our start, the world would devolve so devastatingly. So what do we do of this immense privilege of retreating to go into practice? 

We make sure that privilege is held with as much responsibility and accountability as we are capable of & that we offer powerful and practical practices for this group to become more equipped to meet an ever increasingly complex world.

This retreat became about the part of the ego that is fed on identification and separation - the “I Maker.” There is “what is happening” & then there is “the story about what is happening.” The story will always be laced with ways in which self concept is attempting to enhance itself through… identification and separation.

I am this. I am not this. You are that. You are not that. See me for who I believe myself to be. I will see you for who I believe you to be. And how deeply we hold on to those narratives of separation determines how aggressive, even violent, we become when they are challenged. It’s as proximal as how we look in the mirror and as global as when countries, empires, & governments engage in warfare. 

We came into practices that center awareness and embodiment as paramount to surfacing our unconscious beliefs about our selves and others. We turned toward our own inner narratives first, before considering how that makes manifest in a collective. We learned from the interconnectedness of the nature around us. We found an inner place from which we can take “right action” that supports transformation for the highest good.

How that looks as each student re-enters their lives will be unique to them. Maybe their form of commitment shows up on an algorithmic based form of communication that doesn’t leave much room for nuance or complexity, but probably not. More likely, their change will show up in how we treat each other, how we use money, power, and positioning - and how we engage in policy and with leadership. *We’ll see.*

Until then, THANK YOU incredible loving community & team @emkron @msuar12 @cristina_pacheco @_courtneycrowley_ . May you meet your tests well. LOVE, Aimee + Nat

Living in NYC for the last 20 years, I’ve missed a lot of family gatherings.

If I’m honest, just about all of them.

Yesterday, we celebrated my sister & cousin’s 50th with a big ole reunion and it was the first time in almost 10 years that I’d seen some of my aunts, uncles, cousins, nieces, and nephews. To gather is a true gift.

Probably the most unexpected part of it was how many times a family member and I would embrace and almost instantaneously, they would say some iteration of - I forgot how much you look like your mother - I miss your mom so much - I still talk to your mom every day.

Looking at their faces, memories I hadn’t remembered came flooding back. The way my aunts and uncles share her facial expressions. They way they shepherd and love on the grandkids, and welcome the new partners. Everything had an echo of the way we all knew it at one time.

I shared with them a ring that I wear on my right hand that reminds me of her, that feels like her essence. Inscribed inside: “I will hold you through it all.”

What occurred to me as the night ended is that she continues to hold all of us Igoa’s and all of us Kuhns through these times, even almost ten years after her passing. 

Because she held us each so well during her life, because she was the one so many of us called when we weren’t sure or needed reassurance, 
she holds us still - just by remembering her. 

Even in her death, she teaches us: 

the love of loved ones is always just one memory away.

Aho, may it be so.

✨

Oh how I wanted to send that snappy (fine… bitchy) text to so-and-so to tell them what such-and-such did.

But I went against myself and paused instead.

What part of you, Natalie, wants to feed off this faux form of feasting? What part of you wants to enlarge itself by engorging in gossip?

Not a part I actually want to nourish.
Not a part I actually want to flourish.

That part of me is a youthful hurt that thought gossiping would render me immune from being at the center of another’s. 

That childish kid only knew of how others did it to others, in order to other. And in othering, become together-ed. But together-ed in wound, not care.

In the end, all gossip does 
is keep a story of smallness alive.

Alright, kiddo… soothe another way.
Use restraint. Don’t send the text.
Send a new breath instead.

The younger part quieted,
the future self delighted.

And left in the silence,
she who is proud to grow.
